# SandboxApp — Module Documentation

## Purpose

SandboxApp is the demo/integration-test application that exercises PigeonLib. It is a thin executable target that:

- Provides the `pg::CreateApplication()` entry point required by `EntryPoint.h`.
- Registers two ECS systems against the `pg::World` singleton.
- Supplies its own ECS components (two singleton components, one stale file) and data assets consumed by those systems.

SandboxApp is never built in the `Debug` or `Release` configuration alongside PigeonLib tests; it is the default runnable target when those configurations are active.

---

## Entry Point — `Sandbox2D.cpp`

File: `Code/SandboxApp/Sandbox2D.cpp`

```cpp
class Sandbox : public pg::Application { /* empty — inherits all Application behaviour */ };

pg::Application& pg::CreateApplication()
{
    pg::Application& sandbox = Sandbox::Create();
    pg::World::Get().RegisterSystem(std::make_unique<sbx::ConfigLoaderSystem>());
    pg::World::Get().RegisterSystem(std::make_unique<sbx::SampleUISystem>());
    return sandbox;
}
```

### What it does

1. Calls `Sandbox::Create()` (which delegates to `pg::Application::Create()`), constructing and initialising the application singleton — window, input layer, ImGui layer, clock.
2. Registers two systems onto the `pg::World` ECS. `World::SortSystems()` will topologically order them based on their `DeclareAccess` declarations before the first `Update`.
3. Returns a reference to the application so `EntryPoint.h` can call `app.Run()`.

The `Sandbox` class itself adds nothing over `pg::Application`; it exists only to satisfy the factory pattern that `Application::Create()` requires a concrete type.

